e, larger group interactions, or mass communication—is to attune people to something, be it a shared reality, emotion, or identity. Reconceptualizing the central ideas of pragmatics and semantics, Beaver and Stanley apply their account to a range of phenomena that defy standard frameworks in linguistics and philosophy of language—from dog whistles and covert persuasion to echo chambers and genocidal speech. The authors use their framework to show that speech is inevitably political because all communication is imbued with the resonances of particular ideologies and their normative perspectives on reality.At a time when democracy is under attack, authoritarianism is on the rise, and diversity and equality are being demanded, The Politics of Language offers a powerful new vision of the language of politics, ideology, and protest.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aLanguage and languagesxPolitical aspects. 0aPropaganda. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aA provocative case.  aDavid Beaver.  aJason Stanley.  aThe Politics of Language.  aaffect.  acommunication.  ademocracy.  afirst amendment.  afree speech.  ainformation.  alanguage.  anew view of language.  apolitical.  apolitics.  apowerful speech.  apragmatics.  asemantics.  asocial identity.  aspeech.  athe inherently political nature of language.  atheory of meaning.  awhy speech matters.1 aStanley, Jason, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074974840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691242743?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691242743423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691242743/original  a978-3-11-074974-8  Princeton University Press Comp